TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Performance of Hedge Funds: Risk, Return, and Incentives
AU  - Ackermann, Carl
AU  - McEnally, Richard
AU  - Ravenscraft, David
Y1  - 1999/06/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/06/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.00129
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 833
EP  - 874
VL  - 54
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.00129
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Hedge funds display several interesting characteristics that may influence performance, including: flexible investment strategies, strong managerial incentives, substantial managerial investment, sophisticated investors, and limited government oversight. Using a large sample of hedge fund data from 1988?1995, we find that hedge funds consistently outperform mutual funds, but not standard market indices. Hedge funds, however, are more volatile than both mutual funds and market indices. Incentive fees explain some of the higher performance, but not the increased total risk. The impact of six data-conditioning biases is explored. We find evidence that positive and negative survival-related biases offset each other.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Are Some Mutual Fund Managers Better Than Others? Cross-Sectional Patterns in Behavior and Performance
AU  - Chevalier, Judith
AU  - Ellison, Glenn
Y1  - 1999/06/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/06/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.00130
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 875
EP  - 899
VL  - 54
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.00130
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We examine whether mutual fund performance is related to characteristics of fund managers that may indicate ability, knowledge, or effort. In particular, we study the relationship between performance and the manager's age, the average composite SAT score at the manager's undergraduate institution, and whether the manager has an MBA. Although the raw data suggest striking return differences between managers with different characteristics, most of these can be explained by behavioral differences between managers and by selection biases. After adjusting for these, some performance differences remain. In particular, managers who attended higher-SAT undergraduate institutions have systematically higher risk-adjusted excess returns.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Is Money Smart? A Study of Mutual Fund Investors' Fund Selection Ability
AU  - Zheng, Lu
Y1  - 1999/06/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/06/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.00131
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 901
EP  - 933
VL  - 54
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.00131
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - A previous study finds evidence to support selection ability among active fund investors for equity funds listed in 1982. Using a large sample of equity funds, I find evidence that funds that receive more money subsequently perform significantly better than those that lose money. This effect is short-lived and is largely but not completely explained by a strategy of betting on winners. In the aggregate, there is no significant evidence that funds that receive more money subsequently beat the market. However, it is possible to earn positive abnormal returns by using the cash flow information for small funds.
ER  - 

